Timothy Newsham (newsham@wiliki.eng.hawaii.edu) wrote:
:   crypt(3) is based on DES and used as a one way function.  Basically
: it does DES(0,input), ie encrypt the block of zeros (64 bits of 0)
: with the input (8 bytes, minus parity bits).
: 
: So why does the following give 2 different results?
: 
: [...]
:
: char string1[] = { 
:   0x80, 0x79, 0x6c, 0xd9, 0xc9, 0x02, 0xd5, 0xcf,
: };
: 
: char string2[] = { 
:   0x00, 0x79, 0x6c, 0xd9, 0xc9, 0x02, 0xd5, 0xcf,
: };
: 
: [...]  Is something specially done for bytes that
: are zero?

Indeed it is.  After hacking around with UFC and inserting some debug code,
it was really obvious (of course it is obvious, afterwards :-).
The arguments for crypt(3) are C-strings, and those are _terminated_ by
a zero byte.  So string2 is actually an empty string.

joerg

